04633nam a22007215i 9780857450432DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011003050  a97808574504327 a10.1515/97808574504322doi  a(DE-B1597)636614  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aD802.B38bR45 2011 4aD802.B38bR45 2011 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a940.53/4782221 aRein, Leonid, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Kings and the Pawns :bCollaboration in Byelorussia during World War II /cLeonid Rein. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (458 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWar and Genocide ;v1500tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER 1 COLLABORATION IN OCCUPIED EUROPE: THEORETICAL OVERVIEW -- tCHAPTER 2 HISTORICAL BACKGROUND -- tCHAPTER 3 GERMAN POLICIES IN BYELORUSSIA (1941–1944) -- tCHAPTER 4 BYELORUSSIAN “STATE-BUILDING”: POLITICAL COLLABORATION IN BYELORUSSIA -- tCHAPTER 5 THE CROSS AND THE HOOKED CROSS: THE CHURCH’S COLLABORATION IN OCCUPIED BYELORUSSIA -- tCHAPTER 6 IDEOLOGICAL COLLABORATION IN BYELORUSSIA: THE “LEGAL” PRESS AS A PROPAGANDIST TOOL OF THE NAZIS’ “NEW EUROPE” -- tCHAPTER 7 COLLABORATION IN THE POLITICS OF REPRESSION -- tCHAPTER 8 MILITARY-POLICE COLLABORATION IN BYELORUSSIA -- tSUMMARY -- tAPPENDIX: SS AND MILITARY RANKS -- tGLOSSARY -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX OF PLACES -- tINDEX OF PERSONS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor many years, the history of Byelorussia under Nazi occupation was written primarily from the perspective of the resistance movement. This movement, a reaction to the brutal occupation policies, was very strong indeed. Still, as the author shows, there existed in Byelorussia a whole web of local institutions and organizations which, some willingly, others with reservations, participated in the implementation of various aspects of occupation policies. The very sensitivity of the topic of collaboration has prevented researchers from approaching it for many years, not least because in the former Soviet territories ideological considerations have played an important role in preserving the topic’s “untouchable” status. Focusing on the attitude of German authorities toward the Byelorussians, marked by their anti-Slavic and particularly anti-Byelorussian prejudices on the one hand and the motives of Byelorussian collaborators on the other, the author clearly shows that notwithstanding the postwar trend to marginalize the phenomenon of collaboration or to silence it altogether, the local collaboration in Byelorussia was clearly visible and pervaded all spheres of life under the occupation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCollaborationistszBelarusxHistoryy20th century. 0aNaziszBelarusxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocitieszBelarus. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCollaborationistszBelarus. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zBelarus. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745043240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857450432423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857450432/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK